I wanted to share with the group an app that a friend recommended. I‚Äôve been using it now for a couple of weeks and have been completely mind-blown! The free version allows you to scan a food or cosmetic product and see a detailed description of all harmful substances it contains in a very user-friendly rating format. If you pay the subscription (which is whatever you decide) you can search products. I have to say that I will be rethinking a lot of products that we currently use- from cosmetics that I put on my skin daily to sunscreen brands, breakfast foods that my kids eat all the time‚Ä¶ yikes! https://apps.apple.com/us/app/yuka-food-cosmetic-scanner/id1092799236
I have been using for a while now! Loving it!!
https://www.ewg.org/skindeep/ This is also a really great resource. Very eye openingüò¨ for better or for worseüòÇ

I‚Äôm really sorry you‚Äôre going through this, Laisa.  I don‚Äôt have the exact experience, but I would recommend talking to the Director at your daycare to see how they can help support you both in this transition.

With my youngest, we started in one daycare and only lasted 4 days because it was clear that the Director and assistant director (who I interfaced with) were not supportive during the transition period.

We are at Sunrise now and it has been a totally different experience.  The director and teachers are so helpful ‚Äî especially when we‚Äôve been away and it‚Äôs hard for my son to transition back into the classroom.

Oh no that‚Äôs really hard. How old is the baby and which daycare? Honestly when I see new babies at daycare I see some do cry on and off for the whole day and then by 2 weeks later they are smiling and they are bonded with the teachers. I agree with Val to have a conversation with the director. You can try doing shorter days in the beginning if you could.

Mine was super sensitive during the first two months when he started daycare at 1yo. For the first two weeks or so, he would cry almost all day unless this one teacher came into his class that we spent some time together when we toured the center. My theory is that spending time together when we were around might have given my son a sense of security towards that teacher. So I went pickup earlier and spent some time playing there before going home (not drop off so they don‚Äôt get even more sad when you leave). After building some trust with one of his infant teachers, he would no longer cry when that teacher is present and then he slowly warmed up to other teachers.

She‚Äôs 18 months so a pediatrician! How do I go about getting one? Do I just call around and see who‚Äôs taking patients?

You could try that. But you could also leverage your health insurance to find a pediatrician. Typically they will list which doctors near you accept your insurance and that‚Äôs a good way to find a doctor. There should be a number on your insurance card for help like that, or normally you can log into their website if you made the account etc. But if you call them they can advise you. You could also call doctors directly and ask if they accept your insurance. A lot of people in the north end go to north end waterfront health on Hanover (doctors lopreste, turnock, mcloughlin are all highly regarded) and other places nearby. Lot of options for healthcare which is good.

I personally like using the main hospitals, so either tufts or MGH - that way, when your pediatrician is not in the office, you are still able to see somebody within the group without having to establish care all over again and all your brisk history ends up being in the same computer system that they all have access to
Which is so helpful for late night er or urgent care visits or some day sick appointments
Pediatricians or family physicians.

My only other tip would be to try to get in somewhere that is closest to you‚Ä¶ We were using Tufts in the beginning because we couldn‚Äôt get into MGH. Anyone have advice on how to get rid of cradle cap without their hair falling out with it?! 

I have the Frida comb set, and baby shampoo, and tubby Todd AOO‚Ä¶ I‚Äôve heard they all work great but haven‚Äôt heard about how it works on a baby with hair!! Since my understanding is the cradle cap is just cosmetic, and not harmful, I def don‚Äôt want to treat it if it means his cute hair will come out!

Cleansing oil (or even baby oil will do) on dry hair/scalp. Massage it in, it will loosen the cradle cap and lift it off the scalp. Then you just gently comb it out with very fine-toothed comb and shampoo after. Never lost any hair with that method but got rid of the cap easily.
I‚Äôm

Era Organics Healing Ointment for... https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0194EGJRK?ref=ppx_pop_mob_ap_share

I used this on my daughter who had lots of hair, I would massage it in and leave it in for a day or so and then use a fine tooth comb to brush it out, never had any hair loss

I used olive oil, a small amount and rub gently into babies (dry) scalp. I used a soft toothbrush. I put a little cap on him for like 10 minutes and let it soak in. The flakes soak the oil and lift off. Then I used the very fine tooth comb from the hospital and gently ran across the scalp to lift the flakes. Then I gave a bath and washed his hair using those little silicon pads (like from Frieda baby) to wash the scalp and the oil. You could even not do a bath and just wash the hair on the swaddled baby in the sink like at the salon. I did it daily or every other day until it was resolved. Worked very quickly tho, like 2 or 3 sessions only.

To get rid of cradle cap, I applied olive oil to my son‚Äôs head, placed a plastic bag on top, and put a hat over it. I waited for about an hour. Then, I gave him a bath and used a baby shampoo while combing his hair. Everything came off without any sores or hair loss, and it never came back.
Vaseline/aquaphor worked best for us‚Ä¶ but the hair sure looked greasy after üòÇ

Hi, I just found 1 head lice (louse?) in my 1 year old 's hair! üò≠üò≠ she has baby hair, so it was easy to spot. I thought it was a gnat, but when I took it out and took a photo... it's a lice.

I've heard very good things about this product (from my SIL who is a hairdresser and her kid had lice) ... https://fairytaleshaircare.com/collections/rosemary-repel?gad_source=1&gclid=CjwKCAjw6c63BhAiEiwAF0EH1GqRZuu3t9pNW5QcV-3PmccCYTt7iykQGtWuNo3LqJXVAA3EH3GDRBoCHg0QAvD_BwE
They sell it at Philip's Salon on Hanover Street. I bought the conditioning spray just as a preventative.

Wear your hair in a ponytail daily if it‚Äôs long. Wash and dry on HOT all of her bedding, stuffies, blankets, coats and recent clothes she has worn. If it can‚Äôt be dried on hot then bag it up for 2 weeks. Those things are done to kill any eggs. 

I would also bag up any soft toys and unused blankets for now until it‚Äôs gone so you have less items to worry about washing/drying. If you are worried about your own hair, blow dry it on high heat at the scalp tonight as long as you can tolerate it. The fairy tales shampoo mentioned is great as well. I also always used a tea tree oil shampoo on myself for prevention. Please tell her daycare teachers so they can let the other parents know (and so they can take preventative measures themselves).

https://www.bostonpublicschools.org/UPK

To my knowledge, it‚Äôs offered at some daycares and other small educational institutions and is another free alternative if you don‚Äôt get into the Elliott, Warren Prescott or Harvard Kent in our areas

UPK is program where the city of Boston will pay for a seat at a private school or childcare center for a child of a Boston resident regardless of income level. Applications will open in the spring, BPS will post the exact date some time during the winter, check their page every so often. Starting from the most recent cycle (this past spring) they took away schools‚Äô ability to assign those seats based on the school‚Äôs decision (whatever number of seats the UPK program commits to fund for each school), for example before schools were able to give those seats to siblings of current students. Now it‚Äôs on first-come-first serve basis. So it‚Äôs basically means you get all your required document ready to go on your computer (like birth certificate, residency proof etc.), create your account in the system well in advance, set the alarm and the moment the registration opens you fill it out *as quick as possible* and hit submit button. Do not go back in and edit your form because it will move your spot in line to the later submission time.
This is so helpful to know, as I have company driving in this weekend, thank you! It looks like you just drive in without needing to reserve - is that right?
That's right. We've never had a problem evenings and weekends finding a spot and they have handy public bathrooms in the below ground lobby

Hi all, two travel related questions I‚Äôm hoping someone has experience with! You can bring food! Food is subject to the rule about liquids which TSA defines as anything that will form to the container it‚Äôs in (e.g. peanut butter, pudding, etc.). If you explain to TSA that the food is for kids, they will usually just test it and let you through. 

Netflix, Prime, Disney+, and Hulu all have content you can download as part of your monthly subscription. It‚Äôs housed in the app, but it doesn‚Äôt need any internet connection once downloaded.

Just chiming in! Totally normal to develop fears and how we respond can make all the difference. I like to think about teaching kids why we have fears. Anxiety is normal and natural and can be really helpful because it can help us keep our senses safe. For instance, if we are out hiking and see a bear, feeling anxious helps us figure out if we need to freeze, fight, or run. But sometimes our anxiety fires when there is no real threat (nighttime, being away from a caregiver, etc). Our tendency as parents is to say you‚Äôre safe! Nothing bad will happen! While that reassurance will help reduce anxiety short term, it makes anxiety have more control over us long term. Instead we want to think about being anxiety or bravery detectives, so saying ok, your feel anxious or fearful, let‚Äôs look for clues to see if you‚Äôre really unsafe. Then you can help your child reappraise the fear and realize nothing bad will happen and then you can really help boost them up and praise them for being brave! For instance, ok, you‚Äôre looking under your bed, you don‚Äôt see any monsters. We‚Äôll have to have you go to bed and see if anything bad happens. Wow you woke up and were totally safe! Good job being brave and figuring out there are no monsters under the bed! Believe it or not, even kids at this young age can have impairing levels of anxiety, so if anyone needs more individualized support, happy to help connect you to more resources. Also highly recommend this book written by a wonderful and expert anxiety clinician:https://www.amazon.com/You-Your-Anxious-Child-Worries/dp/1583334955?dplnkId=cb545c73-138c-4783-b262-e088db53bea8&nodl=1

Just chiming in to say that we complete the thinking when my kids are afraid, and it works about 50% of the time. So with the robots throwing you in the trash example, we would say, wow, that does sound super scary. But if someone put you in the trash, what would you do? You‚Äôd probably crawl out again, right? And yell ‚Äúhey, don‚Äôt throw me in the trash robot!‚ÄùAnd then probably take a bath because you‚Äôd be stinky. I find that completing the loop of the story to get to something positive that gives them agency makes them a little less freaked out. But it doesn‚Äôt always work! Sometimes their brains come up with really creepy stuff. Good luck!
Creepy stuff, exactly! Even I get scared üòÖ

If interested in No. End LAX:

The NEAA will be kicking off its third season of lacrosse in March!  The program, under the team name Midnight Riders, will compete in the Mass Youth Lacrosse (MYL) league again this spring.  Both boys and girls teams will be registered with MYL at the 1st/2nd grade level and the 3rd/4th grade level, playing 8 total games on Sunday mornings starting March 30th and running through June 1st.  Home games will be played here in the North End on the Puopolo Park fields while away games will be played in the greater Boston metro area against local opponents.  

The NEAA will also be running its traditional Fundamentals Clinic on Sunday afternoons, which has been a hit amongst kids in the North End the last few years.  Boys and girls ages 4-11 years old are invited to participate in a weekly clinic introducing the fundamentals of lacrosse.  For 6 sessions on Sundays from 3:30-4:45pm, they'll be on the North End fields working through the basics of throwing, catching and scooping a lacrosse ball while blasting music and playing fun kids games.  

To register or ask any questions, you can reach out to the Director of NEAA Lacrosse, David Paolisso @ dpaolisso@gmail.com.  Registration link is: https://www.neaasports.org/register/form/221093232.

I agree with the other moms, but wanted to make an additional recommendation about the burp cloths. I especially loved using muslin cloths - they are light, dry super fast and you can tie them around their neck later on when they start teething/ drooling or as a non-itching scarf. I still have some from 10 years ago- now using them as kitchen towels. 10-15 squares 
 should be enough.

Adding to all the great advice above: the hospital will usually give you the Philips newborn pacifiers so no need to buy those particular ones. For burp cloths, a friend recommending buying a cheap pack of washcloths at Target, and that came in super handy for my girls because they were light weight and super easy to throw in the wash. I forget if it was the birthing class or lactation consultant, but I was told not to cover the hands because they use them to signal when they are hungry (putting them in their mouth) and the scratches aren‚Äôt a big deal (I remember she noted none of us are walking around with scars from scratching ourselves as newborns). But as another mom already noted, keeping up with trimming the nails also works to prevent scratches.
We still have our 30 amazon washcloths from 6 years ago when they were born and we use the for all sorts of things!

For pacifiers, the only thing I'd mention is that we decided to remove them early (~7 months) because one of my girls was becoming so reliant on them and I was worried they would continue needing them into toddlerhood (and there are some dental concerns with pacifiers being used when they're older). That was a TOUGH phase. Long story short: pacifiers are great in the short term but can be difficult to remove later on!

I really liked the wubanub pacifier with the giraffe and lobster, it had enough weight in that little stuffy to help keep the pacifier from slipping out of their mouth since they can't really keep it in as new borns.
Also, footies and mitten cuffs were great because it kept their hands and feet covered while sleeping.

The other thing to consider - have you had any changes in your milk supply? Part of the commando thing (as opposed to naked from the waist down) is about the fact that some kids have trouble pushing down two layers of clothes (rather than one) on their own. K0 - adding 1 (2 total)
K1 - adding 1 (4 total)
K2 - same (4 total)

which means that if you are applying for K0 and K1, you have a better chance than usual. If you are applying to K1 and you don‚Äôt get in, you have close to zero chance to get in the following year in K2, as the 4x K1 classes will take all the spots in the existing 4x K2 classes.
